<h2>Casual vs. Institutional Landlord: Critical Distinction</h2>

<p>A private landlord who owns one or two properties and screens tenants personally is completely different from a property management company managing 500 units for an institutional investor.</p>

<p><strong>Private landlords:</strong> Much more flexible. Many will accept your earnings summary, a brief conversation about your income source, and bank statements. The relationship is personal, and a landlord who speaks with you and believes your income is real may be satisfied with less formal documentation.</p>

<p><strong>Institutional property management:</strong> Uses standardized screening software (RentSpree, AppFolio, Yardi). Often has strict rules about income documentation — must be W-2, must show 3x monthly rent. These companies are hardest for gig workers because there's no human who can make a judgment call.</p>

<p>Before applying to any rental, call ahead and ask: "I work as an independent contractor/gig worker. What income documentation do you accept?" This saves you the application fee if their policy won't accommodate your situation.</p>

